title: JJRC H20W and H20C case organizer

description.text:
I wanted to have my new JJRC H20W drone protected and all the different parts organized, so I bought a case like this:
https://es.aliexpress.com/item/JJRC-H20-RC-Quadcopter-Spare-Parts-Gift-Box/32554606233.html?spm=2114.13010608.0.0.GIbdhe

This case is made for the JJRC H20 and I though that it would fit also my H20W, so I was really disappointed when I received the box and I saw that, tough the drone fits perfectly on the top compartment, my remote controller was bigger than the box itself. So I decided to design something so that I could reuse the box for my drone.

As I was not going to use the bottom part of the box, I also think to use it to store the drone spares, batteries, etc...

On my design you have:

  • A battery holder to store up to 7 batteries and the USB charger
  • A spare separator, which I use to store some spare body shells (http://www.banggood.com/JJRC-H20C-RC-Quadcopter-Spare-Parts-Upper-Body-Cover-Shell-p-1045717.html?rmmds=search)
  • A separator to store the screwdriver and two boxes
  • A box to store spare propellers
  • A box to store other spares
  • Remote control holder which adjust to the lid

The remote holder includes 2 drills to fix it to the lid, but after printing it, I found out that those were not required. Use it if you want.

Boxes have been created using this:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2081840

I hope you like the final result. Any comment is welcomed!!

Enjoy it!!!!

description.text: A sous vide cooker made from a small rice cooker.

Equipment
  • Rice cooker
  • Thermistor
  • 3.3 kÎ© resistor
  • 10 kÎ© resistor
  • Transistor (mine was TIP120)
  • SPDT Relay
  • Diode
  • Extension cord
    • Rice Cooker
    The rice cooker provides many components needed for sous vide cooking. It has a pot for the water bath and a metal plate used for heat transfer. However, it does not allow for arbitrary temperatures to be set and maintained, so for the purpose of the sous vide cooker, we will remove all the electronics. All that should be left is the heating plate, the pot, and the housing. Thermistor
    A thermistor works by varying resistance with changes in temperature. The temperature as a function of resistance is T(R) = {A + Bln(R/Rref) + C[ln(R/Rref)]^2 + D*[(ln(R/Rref)]^2}^(-1) where A through D are constants dependent on the material and Rref is the resistance at a reference temperature. Since I wasn't sure of which exact thermistor I had, I took resistance and temperature measurements for a series of water temperatures. The Arduino checks the temperature using the thermistor but cannot measure the resistance directly. To make up for this, I made a simple voltage divider, or adding a resistor in series to the thermistor, such that the voltage across the thermistor will also change with resistance. The thermistor had a resistance range of roughly 1 - 10 kÎ© during the earlier test. Using this information, I picked a 3.3 kÎ© resistor so that the voltage across the thermistor would vary roughly 2.6 V from min to max. NOTE: If you want to go the easier route, get a LM35/36 temperature sensor. You can skip the voltage divider step, and it's a linear curve!
    http://www.ladyada.net/learn/sensors/tmp36.html Relay
    To heat the water, we need a lot more power than what the Arduino can provide. However, we still want the Arduino to act as a power switch. This is where the relay comes in. The relay I used had five pins. Two are connected to the Arduino and form a circuit internally. Inside there is a coil, and when power runs through it, it flips the relay switch. The other three pins are for the actual switching. The switch can flip between two things, but in this case, we are using it as an off-on. My recommendation is that you test the relay with the Arduino first. When you apply enough power, you should hear a click. Transistor
    My relay can only switch with a minimum [email protected] The Arduino can do 5V but I believe only outputs 40-50mA. I admit, I'm still not entirely sure how transistors work, but they can be used as amplifiers. More information: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cEz1i5xzGEE Wall Plug
    My rice cooker had some extra circuitry for a light and the button to initiate cooking, so I cut that out and away left with a plug. I decided not to use it and instead went with making my own. I bought an extension cord and cut off the female end. I then stripped the wire a bit and then attached one end to the relay and the other to the rice cooker's heating plate. You will complete the circuit using another wire going from the heating plate to the relay. The wall provides a lot of power, so it's important to be safe while doing this step. More information: http://www.sparkfun.com/tutorials/119 Your First Victim
    To be on the safe side, try your new sous vide cooker on an egg first. More information: http://www.edinformatics.com/math_science/science_of_cooking/eggs_sous_vide.htm Improvements
    These are things I would like to do in the future.
  • Create a PCB to house the circuit.
  • Estimate error in thermistor curve fit
  • Timer
    • UPDATE 4/19/12 My thermistor appears to be a bit broken, so I am taking the opportunity to switch it out for an LM35/36 temperature sensor. The new code will be added once it comes in. I am also switching to a solid state relay. LCD is now supported! Mine is a simple 16x2 screen.
    http://arduino.cc/en/Tutorial/LiquidCrystal

comments.text: A nicer solution would be togive a semi-analog output to the heater with PWM. Since it runs on Mains which is AC, you could use an AC-solid state relais (which is basically a triac actuated with an opto coupler) if you somehow detect the zero-crossings of the AC. The alternative is PWM output to the SSR, but keeping the output frequency very low, like 2Hz. That would mean the power is divided into 50 or 60 separate steps, enough resolution for some nice PID control loop.

title: Anet A8 Rear Turbo Fan Mount and Duct
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I was not really looking forward to always having the turbo fan mounted on the front of my j-carriage as it does not really leave me any options to mount an auto leveling sensor or switches or anything really.

So I made a rear fan mount and a custom fan duct to go with it. There is a x end stop pad to ensure that the fan does not hit the frame in the back which means you will have to adjust your x-axis settings at the most by 15 mm but that is not a big deal as the nozzle is still way off the the left of the bed so you don't lose any print area.

All you need is the stock screws to mount it and one of the turbo fan screws to mount the fan since I added an upper peg to support the fan.

This setup allows for the turbo fan to be mounted in the rear of the carriage and the fan duct as well. This now means you can see the nozzle when starting up your prints a lot easier and mount auto leveling sensor in line with the nozzle on the x-axis and only worry about the y-axis offset.

In The Near Future
Making a front carriage assembly to house a auto leveling sensor in line with nozzle as well as a few switches to toggle leds and fans on and off.

And here it is
Anet A8 Front Panel and BLTouch Mount

description.text:
This is a replacement belt grip for the Y belt on the Anet A8. It mounts using the stock holes, screws (M3/18) and nuts. Tensioning the belt with this part is easy. Attach the parts loosely to the printer with enough slack to feed the belt into the toothed gap. Pull the belt to tension and hold the pieces closed. Tighten the screws until all parts are touching. There is no need to over tighten the parts as the teeth keep the belt in place. The temperature of the bed does not seem to affect the part when in use.

Fitment:

12mm spacing on the M3/18 screws. The flat part is a spacer from the bed bracket, the toothed part fits next and the deeply grooved part is used to help tuck the excess belt away. This part is a slightly loose fit for the belt.

I printed this in PLA at 200C and 60C bed on the Anet A8. I have printed 10+ hours of print with no visible degradation. The top cover part is quite thin and can distort if peeled off the print surface carelessly.

Update:
I've added two new models.

  • A thinner Z axis version that has been marked as "thin"
  • A thinner Z axis and narrower version, that has been marked as "narrow-thin"

title: Custom Filament Spool (For drill winding homemade filament!)

description.text:
Since purchasing the Filastruder I needed something to hold the filament I've produced.  I've seen the variable size holders but they require one's self to manually wind up the filament.   I wanted to use a drill and had no empty spools (believe it or not.. lol) except the rep-rapper spools which have a VERY small center to them.  
So I designed this, holds 1kg of filament easily (Pictured holding 1092g)  
Center Spool is 70mm in diameter, 50mm across and 32mm in the center (same as the rep-rapper spools).

Print the following:
Center Spool.stl - qty. 1 - 10% infill, 2 extra shells (3 in total)
Core-washer - qty. 1 - 25% infill, 2 extra shells (3 in total)
Spool Retainer - qty. 2 - 25% infill, 2 extra shells (3 in total) ** The Core-washer only needs to be printed once and can be used over and over for each spool. Required:
  • 5/16" x 4" carriage bolt, washer & nut - mine is galvanized but that's what I had on hand... Any 5/16" carriage bolt will do.

  • 6 5/8" screws - qty. 6 with countersunk heads

  • Cardboard :) - mine is about 1/8" thick, make sure it's quite stiff.
    • Cut 2 cardboard circles (9" in diameter), find the center and use the "core" printed above to trace the hole size. Cut it out using an X-Acto knife. Center the Spool Retainer and punch 3 small holes in each piece of cardboard. Screw the Spool retainers onto the Center Spool on each side. Punch a small hole in the cardboard right next to the retainer to hold the end of the filament. Insert the core into the Center of the spool, put the printed washers on the carriage bolt (1 on each side), place the 5/16" washer on and tighten 5/16" nut (no need for excessive force) Insert the filament and run your drill in reverse so the nut does not undo. Try to keep the filament even as you wind it (I also run it through a cloth in 1 hand to take off any dust). Try not to apply too much force when at the edges as it'll bow out the cardboard.

title: Part Cooler for Prometheus v2 Hotend

description.text:
Part Cooler for the Prometheus v2 Hotend. The design intent is that the part cooler connect directly to the heatsink area of the hotend sandwiched between the heatsink and a 25mm fan. The idea is to keep the parts, size and weight minimal as the person requesting this is using it on a delta printer. That said this part is untested and currently unprinted. Feedback is appreciated.

There are 4 files. The "long" variants are 4mm longer to accomodate two nuts near the nozzle of the hotend. If you only have one nut above the nozzle of the Prometheus hotend you'll be interested in the "short" variants.

The next difference is the air flow. The "no heatsink" variants block any air from the new fan getting to the heatsink. Ie, the new fan provides no additional cooling to the heatsink hence the "no heatsink" name. This means all the air flow from the part cooling fan goes out the duct, you'll likely need to modulate (PWM) the fan speed to prevent over cooling the part. The variants without the "no heatsink" send only part of the fan air flow down to the duct for part cooling. You'll likely set the fan speed higher for this model. This model will also then provide some additional heatsink cooling.

Mount using fan screws that are 10mm longer than the screws for the 25mm fan. Sandwich part cooler between fan and heatsink. Screws go through the fan mount holes, then the part cooler and attach directly into heatsink.
Deisgned in Solidworks using models of the Prometheus hotend and a 25mm fan as reference.

description.text:
There are loads of GoPro mounting accessories around, but I use a standard digital video camera...

I got a GoPro long bendy swan mount and printed this to replace the GoPro mount with a flash size mount that I attach a universal, standard camera tripod mount to!

Loads of fun in FreeCAD working out how to make it! And experimentation with the PLA to get confident it was up to the job.

Printer:

Reprap Prusa i3 2017 model (from kit)

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Notes:

I originally printed the main part in two bits with out supports, but think printing in one is stronger, so printed it 'upside down' so there were a few supports in the 'flash shoe' gap, The nut has a flat side, so thats obvious...
Clean out the support, in the shoe slot. check the threads.

FreeCAD and Calipers.

The standard thread for cameras is an archaic, legacy one that I don't have a tool to design for printing - and I wasn't sure I'd trust PLA that thin to hold a camera. So I went for a flash shoe type mount that you can get adaptors for - also a universal joint making control better.

The rim of the Nut and the end of the thread are bevelled as it tightens to grip the 'ball' in the socket (there is a spherical cut out at the top of the inner hole).

It doesn't hold massively tightly, but stiff enough for the universal joint to do the real aiming work.

The thread bits are pretty thin... but being squashed between the nut and the ball means they can't be flexed that far, and seem to be up to the job.

But put your camera on at your own risk!

description.text:
"One less thing - That's good" - My favorite Forrest Gump quote!

This block can be used to lock-in your Z-limit switch height. This eliminates a critical variable which is the second most likely cause of needing frequent bed re-leveling. (read on for the primary cause and solution).

The block is a 10 sided irregular polyhedron, with the unique property that the opposing faces are each a different dimension. In this case, the five opposing sets of faces provide spacing of 22, 23, 24, 25 and 26 mm. Just turn the block to the size closest to what you need, and slide it under the Z limit switch. Then re-tighten while pressing the switch against the block. Use the bed screws to fine tune the level.

If you need different sizes, just scale this in your slicer before printing.

So what is the actual primary cause of frequently needing to re-level the bed?
The cause is: Loss of Z rod synchronization. This happens when one of the Z rods turns when the other does not. This often occurs when changing filament, due to the large amount of downward force needed to compress the extruder spring. It can also happen if one Z stepper skips and the other does not.

The fix:

  • Turn off the printer or disable the steppers.
  • Use a real level to verify that the x carriage rods are perfectly level (or even better - match the level of the table the printer is on!). Manually turn the Z rod collars until perfect.
  • Make a small mark on the very front of each Z-screw collar. (see second photo)
  • Perform a normal bed leveling. During the process, make sure the marks on the collars stay in sync. (relative to each other). Take time to be precise, because this one should last a while.
  • From this point on, all you need to do is make sure the marks are in the same clock position before starting a print. You can also just turn them both to 6 o'clock. It is best to turn the Z rods while the printer is off or the steppers are disabled.
  • It is especially important to re-sync the Z rods after changing filament.
  • During brim or skirt printing, observe the bead. If you need to raise or drop the bed, turn all 4 bed screws by the exact same amount. I use a screwdriver with a easy to see mark on the handle to keep track of fractional turns.

By using both of these techniques, I have been able to forgo the complexity of adding an auto bed leveling system.

P.S. If you found this useful, then please check out my new product The "OFFi" Auto-off switch for ANET A8 at: http://www.ebay.com/sch/i.html?_nkw=jimb15122
